# resume-tailoring (portable bundle)

This is a single-file `.skill` bundle containing the full resume-tailoring skill and all its
reference files inlined. Drop it into any agent runtime that supports skills-as-prompt
(codex, co-work, Gemini CLI, plain prompt pipelines). For Claude Code, Cursor, Devin,
Windsurf, use the directory form instead — it's equivalent but uses per-file references.

Sections below are separated by `===` delimiters so runtimes that only consume a single
prompt blob still have clear internal structure.

===== SECTION: SKILL.md =====

# /resume-tailoring — Job-Specific Resume Workflow

Build a resume around the whole person, not just the documents on file. Maximize fit to the
target role while keeping every bullet factually defensible.

**Core rule:** Never fabricate experience. Reframe, emphasize, and translate terminology —
do not invent.

**Trigger prompt (canonical):**
```
I want to apply for [Role] at [Company]. Here's the JD: [paste JD or URL]
```

Multi-job mode triggers automatically when the user pastes multiple JDs, multiple URLs, or
says "these roles" / "batch" / "multiple jobs".

## Quick Start

```
/resume-tailoring                              → run full workflow, single job
/resume-tailoring --library ~/resumes          → point at a specific library
/resume-tailoring --batch                      → force multi-job mode
/resume-tailoring --no-docx                    → skip DOCX/PDF, emit markdown only
/resume-tailoring --express                    → skip checkpoints (only after first run)
```

Inputs the skill needs:
1. Job description (text or URL).
2. A resume library: markdown files under `resumes/` in the current dir (or a path the user
   provides). Works with 1 resume; 10+ is ideal.

Outputs written to `resumes/tailored/{Company}_{Role}/`:
- `{Name}_{Company}_{Role}_Resume.md`
- `{Name}_{Company}_{Role}_Resume.docx` (requires `document-skills:docx`)
- `{Name}_{Company}_{Role}_Resume.pdf` (optional)
- `{Name}_{Company}_{Role}_Report.md` — coverage, matches, reframings, interview prep

## Workflow

### Phase 0 — Library Build (always first)

1. Resolve library dir: `--library` flag, else `./resumes/`, else ask. Validate it exists.
2. Glob `*.md`. Announce count: "Building library... found {N} resumes".
3. For each resume, read and parse: contact, roles (company/title/dates), bullets, skills,
   education.
4. Tag each bullet: `themes` (leadership, technical, analytics, strategy…), `metrics`
   (numbers, %, $), `keywords` (action verbs, domain terms), `source_resume`.
5. Detect user preferences: typical length, section order, bullet style.
6. Hold the library in memory as the candidate pool.

If <3 resumes, warn: coverage will be thin; Phase 2.5 discovery especially valuable.

### Phase 1 — Research

Build a success profile. Three sub-steps (see SECTION: research-prompts):
1. Parse JD — must/nice, keywords, implicit prefs, red flags, role archetype.
2. Company research — WebSearch mission/values, blog, news, structure.
3. Role benchmarking — LinkedIn/GitHub profiles of people in similar roles.

If research tools unavailable, fall back to JD-only and tell the user.

**Checkpoint:** Present success profile. Wait for approval.

### Phase 2 — Template

1. Role consolidation — same-company only, never across companies.
2. Title reframing — truthful; emphasize aspect relevant to target. Company/dates exact.
3. Section order — user's library default, unless target role dictates otherwise.
4. Bullet allocation — weight by relevance × recency.

**Checkpoint:** Present skeleton with consolidation, title options, bullet counts.

### Phase 2.5 — Discovery (optional, when gaps found)

Offer when any requirement <60% confidence. 10–15 min branching interview covering
technical, soft-skill, and recent-work gaps. See SECTION: branching-questions.

Capture each experience with: context, scope, addressed gaps, bullet draft, truthfulness
note. Time-box; move on after 2–3 dry attempts. Never pressure.

### Phase 3 — Assembly

Score every candidate bullet per template slot (see SECTION: matching-strategies):

```
Overall = 0.4·Direct + 0.3·Transferable + 0.2·Adjacent + 0.1·Impact
```

Bands: 90+ DIRECT · 75–89 TRANSFERABLE · 60–74 ADJACENT · 45–59 WEAK · <45 GAP.

Show top 3 per slot with source resume + any reframing proposals (with truthfulness note).
For gaps: reframe / omit / cover-letter / re-run discovery.

**Checkpoint:** Present full mapping + coverage summary.

### Phase 4 — Generation

Write to `resumes/tailored/{Company}_{Role}/`:
1. Markdown resume.
2. DOCX via `document-skills:docx` — Calibri 11/12pt, 0.5–1in margins, proper bullet config,
   bold for company/title/dates. Never unicode bullets.
3. PDF (if requested / DOCX succeeds).
4. Generation report — target summary, coverage metrics, before/after reframings with
   truthfulness notes, source breakdown, remaining gaps + recommendations, interview prep.

DOCX failure → fall back to markdown only; note in report.

### Phase 5 — Save + Learn (conditional)

Options: (1) Save to library, (2) Revise, (3) Save locally only.

On save: move artifacts into library, re-parse, persist `.meta.json` with scores,
reframings, discoveries, coverage. Future runs start richer.

## Multi-Job Mode

Triggers on multiple JDs. See SECTION: multi-job-workflow.

Phases: Intake → Aggregate gap analysis → Shared discovery → Per-job processing →
Batch finalization. Incremental additions supported.

Typical savings: 11% (3 jobs), 27% (5 jobs), 33% (7 jobs).

## Checkpoints

- End of Phase 1 — success profile
- End of Phase 2 — template skeleton
- End of Phase 3 — content mapping + coverage
- End of Phase 4 — file review before library save

`--express` skips 1–3; use only for repeat batch applications.

## Truthfulness Rules (non-negotiable)

- Never invent a role, company, date, metric, or skill.
- Never inflate seniority beyond what scope defends.
- Reframe, don't fabricate — same facts, different emphasis and terminology.
- Disclose gaps honestly; offer cover-letter recommendations rather than padding.
- Every reframing has before/after + reason in the report.

## Edge Cases

- Tiny library (<3 resumes): warn, lean on discovery.
- Critical gap <60% on must-have: reframe / discovery / cover-letter / omit — never force.
- Research fails: JD-only fallback; ask user for context; proceed best-effort.
- Vague JD: extract what's possible, ask for missing context, proceed.
- Overflow >2 pages: rank bullets, propose cuts, user decides.
- Career gap: frame legitimately; surface skills via discovery.

===== SECTION: research-prompts =====

# Research Prompts

Templates for Phase 1 (success profile building).

## 1. JD Parsing

```
Parse this job description. Extract:
1. EXPLICIT REQUIREMENTS — must-have vs nice-to-have
2. TECHNICAL KEYWORDS — stacks, tools, domains, methodologies
3. IMPLICIT PREFERENCES — cultural signals, hidden expectations
4. RED FLAGS — overqualification, scope creep, unrealistic combos
5. ROLE ARCHETYPE — IC technical / people leadership / cross-functional / hybrid
6. SENIORITY SIGNALS — scope, autonomy, ambiguity, headcount implied

JD: {JD_TEXT}

Return structured sections, terse bullets.
```

## 2. Company Research

WebSearch queries (parallel):
- `{company} mission values culture`
- `{company} engineering blog`
- `{company} recent news product launches`
- `{company} team structure engineering`

Technical roles also:
- `{company} tech stack`
- `site:news.ycombinator.com {company}`

Synthesis:
```
From these search results, extract:
1. Mission and stated values
2. Cultural priorities
3. Business model, customer base, revenue stage
4. Company stage (startup / growth / mature) and implications
5. Recent strategic moves that affect this team
Results: {SEARCH_RESULTS}
```

## 3. Role Benchmarking

Strategy:
1. WebSearch `site:linkedin.com {title} {company}`
2. WebFetch top 3–5 profiles
3. Fallback: `site:linkedin.com {title} {peer_company}`
4. Double fallback: GitHub search for engineers at {company} with similar titles

Analysis:
```
Analyze these profiles for people doing similar work:
1. Common backgrounds and career paths
2. Emphasized skills and project types
3. Terminology patterns
4. Notable accomplishments / narrative themes
5. Anti-patterns — backgrounds that look different
Profiles: {PROFILE_DATA}
```

## 4. Success Profile Synthesis

```markdown
## Success Profile: {Role} at {Company}

### Core Requirements (Must-Have)
- {Requirement}: evidence from {JD/research}

### Valued Capabilities (Nice-to-Have)
- {Capability}: why it matters in this context

### Cultural Fit Signals
- {Value}: how a candidate demonstrates it

### Narrative Themes
- {Theme}: typical examples from role holders

### Terminology Map
Standard term → Company-preferred term

### Risk Factors
- {Concern}: mitigation strategy for the resume

### Red-Flag Checks
- Things to avoid / claims that would hurt credibility
```

Present at checkpoint with top findings and ask for adjustments.

## Graceful Degradation

If WebSearch is unavailable or sparse:
```
Limited external research available — {reason}.
- JD analysis: full
- Company research: {partial / missing}
- Role benchmarking: {partial / missing}

Proceeding with JD-driven analysis. If you can share culture/team/stack context, that'll
improve the template. Remaining uncertainty noted in generation report.
```

===== SECTION: matching-strategies =====

# Matching Strategies

## Scoring Formula

```
Overall = 0.4·Direct + 0.3·Transferable + 0.2·Adjacent + 0.1·Impact
```

### Direct (40%) — same skill, domain, technology, outcome
- 90–100: exact match
- 70–89: same skill, different domain
- 50–69: keyword/outcome overlap only
- <50: weak

### Transferable (30%) — same capability, different context
- 90–100: process/skill generic, transfers cleanly
- 70–89: light translation needed
- 50–69: analogy required
- <50: stretch

### Adjacent (20%) — secondary responsibility, related tools, related problem space
- 90–100: same thing, different name
- 70–89: clearly related
- 50–69: requires explanation
- <50: loose

### Impact (10%) — achievement type matches role's impact lens
- 90–100: perfect alignment
- 70–89: strong
- 50–69: moderate
- <50: weak

### Bands
- 90+ DIRECT — use with confidence
- 75–89 TRANSFERABLE — strong
- 60–74 ADJACENT — reframe
- 45–59 WEAK — only if nothing better
- <45 GAP — flag, don't force

## Reframing Strategies (only when ≥60 and terminology is off)

1. **Keyword alignment** — preserve meaning, swap vocabulary
   ```
   "Led experimental design and data analysis programs"
   → "Led data science programs combining experimental design and statistical analysis"
   ```
2. **Emphasis shift** — same facts, different focus
   ```
   "Designed statistical experiments... saving millions in recall costs"
   → "Prevented millions in potential recall costs through predictive risk detection using
      statistical modeling"
   ```
3. **Abstraction level** — up or down on technical specificity
   ```
   "Built MATLAB-based automated evaluation system"
   → "Developed automated evaluation system"  (language-agnostic target)
   or → "Built automated evaluation system (MATLAB, Python)"  (stack-heavy target)
   ```
4. **Scale emphasis** — highlight the scale dimension the target cares about
   ```
   "Managed project with 3 stakeholders"
   → "Led cross-functional initiative coordinating 3 organizational units"
   ```

Every reframing must be disclosed with before/after + truthfulness note in the report.

## Title Reframing

- Emphasize a different aspect: "Graduate Researcher" → "Research Software Engineer"
- Industry-standard terminology: "Scientist III" → "Senior Research Scientist"
- Truthful specialization: "Engineer" → "ML Engineer" (if ML substantial)
- Seniority indicator: Lead / Senior / Staff based on defensible scope

Constraints: company/dates exact; core responsibilities must match reality; never claim
seniority scope can't defend.

Present 2 options with rationale; user picks.

## Role Consolidation

Consolidate same-company roles when:
- Responsibilities overlap heavily
- Target values continuity over granular progression
- Combined narrative stronger
- Page space tight

Keep separate when:
- Different companies (always)
- Dramatically different responsibilities that both matter
- Target values progression story
- One position much more relevant

## Gap Handling (<60% on must-have)

Four options, in order:
1. Reframe adjacent bullet (only if reframe is honest)
2. Run Phase 2.5 discovery
3. Omit slot, reallocate space, disclose in report
4. Acknowledge in cover letter

Never fabricate. Flag + recommend cover-letter framing + interview prep.

===== SECTION: branching-questions =====

# Branching Questions

Discovery is a conversation, not a questionnaire.

## Principles

1. Start broad, go narrow.
2. Branch on the answer.
3. Time-box 10–15 min; move on after 2–3 dry attempts.
4. Cross-reference across gaps.
5. Capture in structure.
6. Truth bar stays high.

## Multi-Job Leverage Prefix

```
"{SKILL} appears in {N} of your target jobs ({Company1}, {Company2}).
This is a {HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW}-LEVERAGE gap — addressing it helps {all/some/one} application(s).
Current best match: {X}% ('{best_match_text}').
{Standard probe below}"
```

HIGH 3+ · MEDIUM 2 · LOW 1.

## Pattern A — Technical Skill Gap

PROBE: "The role requires {SKILL}. Have you worked with {SKILL} or {ADJACENT}?"

- A1 YES → "What did you use it for? Scale? Production? Challenges? Metrics?"
- A2 INDIRECT → "What was your role in the {SKILL} work? Did you {a1}/{a2}/{a3}? What did
  you learn?"
- A3 ADJACENT TECH → "Tell me about {ADJACENT_TECH}. Did you {relevant_activity}?"
- A4 PERSONAL/LEARNING → "Side projects, courses? What did you build? How recent?"
- A5 COMPLETE NO → "Any {broader_category} work?" → If yes explore, else move on.

## Pattern B — Soft Skill / Experience Gap

PROBE: "The role emphasizes {SOFT_SKILL}. Tell me about times you've {demonstrated_skill}."

- B1 STRONG → "Entities? Challenge? How drove? Result? Obstacles?"
- B2 VAGUE → Reframe probe, ask about scope and what made it challenging.
- B3 PROJECT-SPECIFIC → "Tell me more. Your role vs others? How did you ensure alignment?"
- B4 VOLUNTEER/SIDE → "Scope? Timeline? Relevant skills? Measurable outcomes?"

## Pattern C — Recent Work Probe

PROBE: "What have you worked on in the last 6 months that isn't on your resume yet?"

- C1 DESCRIBES PROJECT → "Your role? Tech? Problem? Impact? Addresses {gap_area}?"
- C2 MULTIPLE → "Walk through each. Start with {first}."
- C3 "NOTHING NEW" → "Small improvements? Process changes? Learning? Mentoring?
  Anything that seems too small?"

## Capture Template

```markdown
### Discovery {n}: {Brief description}
- Context: {where/when}
- Scope: {scale, duration, impact}
- Addresses: {gap name(s)}, leverage: HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW
- Bullet draft: "{Achievement-focused bullet}"
- Confidence: {% gap filled}
- Truthfulness note: {why defensible}
- Integration: ADD-TO-RESUME / ADD-TO-LIBRARY / REFINE / DISCARD
```

## Hand-off

After discovery, ask per-experience:
```
Captured {N} new experiences. For each:
1. ADD TO CURRENT RESUME
2. ADD TO LIBRARY ONLY
3. REFINE FURTHER
4. DISCARD
How should I handle each?
```

===== SECTION: multi-job-workflow =====

# Multi-Job Workflow

Batch for 3–5 similar roles. Shared library + shared discovery + per-job research/match/gen.

## Trigger

- Multiple JDs/URLs pasted
- "multiple jobs", "these roles", "batch", "3 jobs", "5 positions"
- `--batch` flag

Offer choice:
```
I see {N} JDs. Multi-job mode:
  - Shared discovery (ask once, apply to all)
  - Aggregate gap analysis
  - Per-job research/template/matching kept separate
10–30% faster than sequential. Use multi-job? (Y/N)
```

## Phase 0 — Intake & Batch Init

Per job: JD, company, role, priority (H/M/L, default M), notes. Assign job_id = job-N.
Quick-parse JD: must-reqs, keywords, soft skills, domains (no full research yet).

Create `resumes/batches/batch-{date}-{slug}/` with `_batch_state.json`,
`_aggregate_gaps.md`, `_discovered_experiences.md`.

_batch_state.json schema:
```json
{
  "batch_id": "batch-YYYY-MM-DD-slug",
  "created": "ISO8601",
  "current_phase": "intake|gap_analysis|discovery|per_job|finalization",
  "processing_mode": "interactive|express",
  "jobs": [
    {
      "job_id": "job-1",
      "company": "...", "role": "...",
      "jd_text": "...", "jd_url": "...",
      "priority": "high|medium|low",
      "notes": "...",
      "status": "pending|processing|ready_for_review|approved",
      "requirements": [...],
      "gaps": [...]
    }
  ],
  "discoveries": [...],
  "aggregate_gaps": {...}
}
```

Run library init once for the whole batch.

**Checkpoint:** Confirm batch complete.

## Phase 1 — Aggregate Gap Analysis

1. First-pass match every requirement × library. Flag <60%.
2. Dedupe by name across jobs.
3. Leverage: HIGH 3+ · MEDIUM 2 · LOW 1.

Write `_aggregate_gaps.md` with ranked gaps.

**Checkpoint:** Show gap map; decide discovery now or defer.

## Phase 2 — Shared Discovery

Single interview covering HIGH then MEDIUM leverage. LOW usually handled per-job via
reframing or cover letter.

Use branching-questions patterns with leverage prefix. Write to
`_discovered_experiences.md`. Tag each with `applies_to_jobs: [...]`. Merge into library.

## Phase 3 — Per-Job Processing (sequential, priority order)

For each job: Research → Template → Matching (enriched library) → Generation → status
`ready_for_review`.

Modes:
- Interactive (default) — checkpoints per job
- Express (`--express` after first) — skip checkpoints; review at finalization

## Phase 4 — Batch Finalization

```
Batch summary — {N} resumes ready
| Job | Company | Role | Coverage | Direct | Gaps |
|-----|---------|------|----------|--------|------|

Actions: REVIEW ALL / REVIEW {job_id} / APPROVE BATCH / REVISE {job_id}
```

On approve: move artifacts into library, rebuild with enriched content + metadata, preserve
batch state for incremental adds.

## Incremental Additions

Load existing batch + discoveries. Quick-parse new JDs. Incremental gap analysis (only new
gaps). Mini-discovery. Process new jobs through Phase 3.

Typical: 2-job add after 3-job batch ≈ 20 min vs 30 min fresh.

## Time Model

| Jobs | Sequential | Batch | Savings |
|-----|-----------|-------|---------|
| 3   | 45 min    | 40    | 11%     |
| 5   | 75 min    | 55    | 27%     |
| 7   | 105 min   | 70    | 33%     |

Savings depend on similarity. Overlap <40% → fall back to sequential.

## Failure Modes

- Low overlap (<20% dedup benefit) → tell user, offer sequential.
- Discovery fatigue → pause, save state, resume later.
- Per-job research failure → degrade to JD-only for that job, continue batch.
- DOCX fails for one job → MD + report, flag in summary.

===== END OF BUNDLE =====
